Additional details

The GE Cync Smart Bulb Color Changing Indoor LED Lights that are Matter compatible make it easy to enhance your room light or to celebrate the holidays. Use millions of colors to decorate for each holiday, create the perfect party vibe, and support your team on game day with each Cync light bulb. Find the right aesthetic décor for your gaming room, improve your LED work light, or use our LED light bulbs as bedroom lights. These indoor light bulbs feature a tunable white spectrum, allowing you to get the perfect hue that highlights your home's landscaping and architecture. Get additional confidence by scheduling your Cync smart lights to turn on so that you improve home security and never come home to a dark house. With voice control through Matter and the ability to control your lights away from home, you'll get the added convenience of controlling each WiFi bulb while you’re away on vacation or when your hands are full. Our Matter compatible light bulbs pair easily with leading smart home apps such as Amazon Alexa, Google Assistant, Samsung SmartThings, and Apple Home devices (sold separately) for hands-free control - no hub required.

    5.0 out of 5 starsVerified Purchase
    so cool! works great with the cync app and google assistant
    Reviewed in the United States on October 11, 2024
    Color: MulticolorSize: 2 Bulbs (Pack of 1)
    The color range is good. There's a range of the blue color that has an almost blacklight effect. I've been using the same three regular single color Cync bulbs in the living room for several years, so I'm not worried about longevity, etc. I got these RGB bulbs... See more
    The color range is good. There's a range of the blue color that has an almost blacklight effect. I've been using the same three regular single color Cync bulbs in the living room for several years, so I'm not worried about longevity, etc. I got these RGB bulbs for two bedrooms.
    So. Freaking. Cool.
    The google assistant only understands base colors, so for fine tuning color you need to use the Cync app manually. So far Google has been able to use primary colors, plus teal, purple and pink AND some of the Cync lighting effects (Vegas, party, etc). I still have a lot of testing to do to map out all the capabilities, but sometimes Google Assistant "doesn't understand" a color or effect request - "Ok google, set bedroom 1 to red. Ok Google set bedroom 1 to 50%" "Ok Google, set all lights to 30%" etc, etc.

    Speaking of the Cync app, setup is ridiculously simple and it updates the devices to the latest firmware when you first setup them up in the app. Integration with Google Assistant (and I'm assuming Alexa) is really simple as well. Also in the Cync app, the "routines" are fabulous. I have the living room lights set to come on at 40% at sunset (as determined by zip code) and go off at midnight. I set the bedroom lights to match the morning alarm times we have setup. The lights will come on to red a minute before my alarm sounds in the morning. (red is the best color, easiest on they eyes, to wake up to. that's science.)

    I'm really very happy with this purchase at the Prime Day price of $13, but it's easily worth the regular asking price.
    The only possible way these Cync A19 Smart LED bulbs could be better is if they had a 100W equivalent version, but I am happy with the 60W product.
    4 people found this helpful

    4.0 out of 5 starsVerified Purchase
    Great colors, connectivity a little inconsistent
    Reviewed in the United States on January 2, 2024
    Color: MulticolorSize: 2 Bulbs (Pack of 1)
    I have 4 of these bulbs, two are paired as one in a single fixture located in a bedroom, and two are in separate fixtures on opposite walls in my living room. I like the color choices and ability to save colors you like to switch between. One light is set to come on daily... See more
    I have 4 of these bulbs, two are paired as one in a single fixture located in a bedroom, and two are in separate fixtures on opposite walls in my living room. I like the color choices and ability to save colors you like to switch between. One light is set to come on daily for a certain period of time, and besides once it has always turned on and off as programmed.

    I only use the Cync app (on an iphone). I dont have any other Alexa or Google home devices so I found using the Google home app pointless. Cync app seems to do everything I want.

    My only complaint is when I want to tweak/adjust the lights I have to be in the room with them. So my two living room lights can only be adjusted from in there, and the bedroom lights can only be adjusted if youre in the room, or right outside the door. The app tends to only communicate well when you are near the bulb you want to adjust. This isnt a deal breaker for me, but I live in a small house so it seems like connectivity wouldnt be an issue. My other WIFI devices get a strong signal in those rooms.

    Maybe the flaw is with the Cync app. I guess its possible it only wants to connect to the bulbs via bluetooth when making adjustments, and therefore has trouble communicating with that large of a radius simultaneously. But supposedly they use WIFI and bluetooth. I’m just not sure how the technology is being utilized.

    Update: Everything is working perfectly now. My problem was the first bulbs I setup were a little further from my wifi router than the others, and I guess the bulbs create some sort of mesh network allowing them to work together and stay interconnected. Must be a Cync thing. Bottomline all I had to do was remove/delete the pair I setup first, which made one of the bulbs closer to my router the sorta main communicator or creator of the mesh network. Added the bulb pair back, and now everything works great. Lights are controllable from anywhere I have a network connection from the Cync app. Think I’ll leave my rating at 4 stars though.

  • Drew Long
    3.0 out of 5 starsVerified Purchase
    Bulbs work good with Alexa, but app is terrible
    Reviewed in the United States on July 22, 2022
    Color: MulticolorSize: 2 Bulbs (Pack of 1)
    My first time installing these was pretty easy, I just downloaded the app and followed the instructions and was able to connect them to Wi-Fi alright. They responded well to the app and I could do lots of stuff like change the brightness and color, save specific colors,... See more
    My first time installing these was pretty easy, I just downloaded the app and followed the instructions and was able to connect them to Wi-Fi alright. They responded well to the app and I could do lots of stuff like change the brightness and color, save specific colors, change individual bulb settings, etc. the reason I bought the bulbs though was so I could set a schedule that would turn them on at a certain time with a certain color. It wasn’t too difficult to setup a schedule, and there were videos online to help, but whenever I set the schedule it didn’t go off. I started with ones just a few minutes in advance so that I could see them going off to make sure they worked, but they just weren’t coming on at the time I told it to. Eventually I set one and let it go for a bit, and it eventually came on like 10 minutes later. So I realized that they actually were working, the time just want synced well on the bulbs.
    I then tried to factory reset the bulbs to see if setting them up again would fix the time issue. This process wasn’t to bad but you have to watch the video to figure out how to reset them. When I tried to set them back up though, there was always one bulb that wouldn’t connect to Wi-Fi. I tried like 5 times resetting them and trying to set them back up, and each time one of the bulbs wouldn’t connect. I eventually let it alone for a day and tried again, and thankfully it worked. I figured out that if I let the bulb run for too long I think something with it being to hot interferes with the Wi-Fi setup. So if you are having problems with connecting the Wi-Fi, let it cool down a bit and then quickly set it up right after you turn them on.
    Still after resetting them several times, there was always some weird problem with the scheduling feature that wouldn’t work the way I wanted them too. So eventually I just connected them to Alexa and setup a schedule through the Alexa app. This has worked fantastically and without any problems. You might have to set multiple schedules in order to accomplish something though because there are less features you can do through the Alexa app. For example if you want the light to come on at a low brightness and ramp up with a different color, then you have to use two schedules for changing the color and doing the brightness ramp. Also note that if the bulb has physically been turned off with the switch, it must be turn back on for a few minutes before Alexa can find it and control it.
    Overall these bulbs have done what I need them too through the Alexa app, but I have not found the Cync app to be useful beside just changing the brightness and color manually. If these bulbs are on sale they may be worth it because they are cheap, but I would look elsewhere first for a bulb with a better app integration.
